# Lantern dev/prod environment variables.
#
# Copy this file to .env.local (gitignored) and fill in the values you need.
# `make run-api` and the other run-* targets auto-load .env.local at startup.
#
# ============================================================================
# FORMAT NOTES — read these before editing!
# ============================================================================
#
# - Values MUST be UNQUOTED. Make's `include .env.local` treats `FOO="bar"`
#   as the literal string `"bar"` (with quotes baked in), which then gets
#   exported and breaks every consumer. Use plain `FOO=bar`.
# - No spaces around `=`. `FOO = bar` (with spaces) silently fails.
# - Multi-line values aren't supported. If you need one, write it as a
#   single line with `\n` escapes — the consumers strip them.
# - This file is plain text. Anything pasted here lives in your shell
#   history and any backup. Rotate secrets that have been through chat.

# ============================================================================
# LLM ROUTING
# ============================================================================

# Free local dev: route LLM calls through your local Claude Code CLI
# (uses Claude Max subscription, no API credits burned). Requires
# `claude` on $PATH. When tools are needed (agents with connected
# integrations), the failover chain skips claude-code automatically.
#LANTERN_USE_CLAUDE_CODE=1

# Override the `claude` binary location if it's not on $PATH.
#LANTERN_CLAUDE_BINARY=/usr/local/bin/claude

# Auto-routing strategy: balanced (default), cheap, quality, fast.
# `balanced` weights quality heavily; `cheap` will route to gpt-4o-mini
# / haiku and may flake on tool calls.
#LANTERN_ROUTE_STRATEGY=balanced

# ============================================================================
# OAUTH — GOOGLE
# ============================================================================
#
# Google issues ONE OAuth client per Cloud project. The same client unlocks:
#   - /auth/oauth/google login (Sign in with Google)
#   - Gmail connector (read inbox, send mail)
#   - Google Calendar connector
#   - Google Drive connector
#   - Google Sheets connector
#
# Set up:
#   1. https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/credentials → Create OAuth 2.0
#      Client ID (type: Web application).
#   2. Add authorized redirect URIs:
#        http://localhost:8080/auth/oauth/google/callback     (for login)
#        http://localhost:8080/v1/connectors/oauth/callback   (for connectors)
#   3. Enable the APIs you need:
#        https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/library/gmail.googleapis.com
#        https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/library/calendar-json.googleapis.com
#        https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/library/drive.googleapis.com
#        https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/library/sheets.googleapis.com
#   4. Paste credentials below (unquoted).
#GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=
#GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=

# ============================================================================
# OAUTH — PER-CONNECTOR
# ============================================================================
#
# Generic pattern: OAUTH_CLIENT_ID_<CONNECTOR> and the matching _SECRET.
# Connector ID is uppercased and dashes replaced with underscores:
#   slack  → OAUTH_CLIENT_ID_SLACK / OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET_SLACK
#   github → OAUTH_CLIENT_ID_GITHUB / OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET_GITHUB
#   notion → OAUTH_CLIENT_ID_NOTION / OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET_NOTION
#
# Redirect URI for all: http://localhost:8080/v1/connectors/oauth/callback
#
# Without OAuth env vars, the connector still works via manual install
# (paste API key / Bot Token / PAT in the dashboard).
#
#OAUTH_CLIENT_ID_GITHUB=
#OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET_GITHUB=
#OAUTH_CLIENT_ID_SLACK=
#OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET_SLACK=
#OAUTH_CLIENT_ID_NOTION=
#OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET_NOTION=

# Public base URL for OAuth redirects. Change in prod.
#OAUTH_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8080

# ============================================================================
# LLM PROVIDER KEYS (used when claude-code routing is off)
# ============================================================================
#
# These are read by the control-plane as a fallback for tenants that
# haven't configured their own keys in /settings. Get them at:
#   https://console.anthropic.com/settings/keys
#   https://platform.openai.com/api-keys
#
# IMPORTANT: a Claude Max or ChatGPT Plus subscription does NOT include API
# credits — those are billed separately at console.anthropic.com and
# platform.openai.com. See /v1/completions errors for details.
#ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=
#OPENAI_API_KEY=

# ============================================================================
# WHATSAPP BRIDGE → CONTROL-PLANE AUTH
# ============================================================================
#
# Bridge needs to call the control-plane to create sessions + dispatch
# messages. Either set a long-lived service token OR provide credentials
# the bridge will use to auto-login (and auto-relogin on 401).
#
# Static service token (preferred for prod — long-lived, no password):
#LANTERN_API_TOKEN=
#
# Or auto-login mode — bridge logs in at startup AND re-logs on 401.
# Defaults to admin@lantern.dev / lantern in dev so the bridge works out
# of the box. Override for any non-dev deployment.
#LANTERN_BRIDGE_EMAIL=admin@lantern.dev
#LANTERN_BRIDGE_PASSWORD=lantern

# Where the bridge finds the control-plane (override for multi-host prod).
#LANTERN_API_URL=http://localhost:8080

# Bridge listen config.
#LANTERN_BRIDGE_BIND=127.0.0.1
#LANTERN_BRIDGE_PORT=3100
# Shared token that gates the bridge's REST + WebSocket surface. When set,
# the dashboard must send the same value as Authorization: Bearer <token>.
#LANTERN_BRIDGE_TOKEN=
# CORS origin allowed to call the bridge directly.
#LANTERN_BRIDGE_ORIGIN=http://localhost:3001

# Optional: bridge sends periodic heartbeats to control-plane so the
# dashboard sees fresh pairing state even when proxying through different
# hosts. Both vars must be set; either alone is a no-op.
#LANTERN_CONTROL_PLANE_URL=http://localhost:8080
#LANTERN_BRIDGE_HEARTBEAT_TOKEN=

# ============================================================================
# WHATSAPP BRIDGE — BEHAVIOR TUNING
# ============================================================================

# How long the bot stays silent for a contact after the owner types in
# their thread (rolling takeover). Minutes; default 60.
#LANTERN_AGENT_PAUSE_MIN=60

# Attention classifier dedup window. Don't notify the owner about the same
# urgent contact more than once per N minutes. Default 30.
#LANTERN_ATTENTION_DEDUP_MIN=30

# Display name used in self-chat prompts ("It's Shekhar's WhatsApp...").
#LANTERN_OWNER_NAME=Shekhar

# Agent identity sent on session creation. Default: whatsapp-assistant.
#LANTERN_AGENT_NAME=whatsapp-assistant

# System-prompt augmentation included in every WhatsApp turn.
#LANTERN_SYSTEM_PROMPT=You are Shekhar's WhatsApp assistant. Be brief.

# ============================================================================
# WHATSAPP BRIDGE — STATUS DELIVERY FALLBACKS
# ============================================================================
#
# When WhatsApp's Signal session falls into 'Waiting for this message'
# limbo, the bridge's /lantern responses + /bot confirmations stop
# reaching your phone. Configure ONE OR MORE of the channels below and
# the bridge mirrors every status reply to them. Pick whatever you
# actually use:

# --- Email mirror (universal, recommended) ---
# Routes via your already-configured Gmail connector at /connectors.
# Subject = first line of the reply ("Lantern · 🟢 active"). Throttled
# to one email per unique-text per 30s and skips short reactions.
#LANTERN_OWNER_EMAIL=

# --- Telegram bot mirror ---
#
# When WhatsApp's Signal session is in a stale-key 'Waiting for this
# message' loop, bridge replies still need to reach you on your phone.
# Configure a Telegram bot here and every /lantern reply, /bot
# confirmation, pairing notification, etc. ALSO arrives via Telegram
# instantly with no E2E key issues.
#
# Setup (90 seconds):
#   1. On Telegram, message @BotFather → /newbot → follow prompts
#      → paste the bot token below.
#   2. Send your new bot any message ("hi") from your account.
#   3. Get your chat id: open
#      https://api.telegram.org/bot<TOKEN>/getUpdates and look for
#      result[0].message.chat.id (an integer). Paste below.
#
# Unset = silently disabled; the bridge still tries WhatsApp only.
#LANTERN_OWNER_TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=
#LANTERN_OWNER_TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID=

# ============================================================================
# INFRASTRUCTURE (typically set by docker-compose, not .env.local)
# ============================================================================

#DATABASE_URL=postgres://lantern:lantern@localhost:5432/lantern?sslmode=disable
#REDIS_URL=redis://localhost:6379
#S3_ENDPOINT=http://localhost:9000
#LOG_LEVEL=info
